<subSubSection id="9F4BEF23CF36633C28C9CFC343484DE7" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="BBD95ABDAF522D3866797A4E1890131D" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicName id="272D18EE137549D24EBD3F6ECAD8CDD0" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypselosyrphus</taxonomicName>
Hull, 1937a: 21. Type species 
<taxonomicName id="1FD30301414C6E9D0BE13C7D968A8B8B" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus trigonus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigonus">Hypselosyrphus trigonus</taxonomicName>
Hull, 1937: 21, by original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CBC8137AAE25468B1A0B61204FE554A1" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph id="039CCFCBBD7C48A59B9065CBC4715253" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D3BDAED8684F0DDAF82B19E8DD70585" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Body length: 7-10 mm. Stingless bee mimicking flies with short to moderately long antennae and oval to triangular abdomen. Head slightly wider than thorax. Face convex; narrower than an eye. Lateral oral margins not produced. Vertex narrow, in most species convexly produced and shining, flat in some species. Occiput narrow over entire length, except ventrally strongly widened in 
<taxonomicName id="CB768DBF459F07EBBF6DAC929B38DB0F" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus ulopodus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ulopodus">Hypselosyrphus ulopodus</taxonomicName>
. Eye with short, sparse pile. Eye margins in male strongly converging at level of frons, with mutual distance smaller than width of antennal fossa, except 3 times as wide in 
<taxonomicName id="673BB2435ECAE747F9453B00F5F2AA98" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus ulopodus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ulopodus">Hypselosyrphus ulopodus</taxonomicName>
. Antennal fossa about as wide as high. Antenna as long as or shorter than distance between antennal fossa and anterior oral margin; basoflagellomere shorter to longer than scape, oval; bare. Postpronotum pilose. Scutellum semicircular, triangular or apicomedially sulcate; without calcars. Anepisternum without or with weak sulcus; pilose anterodorsally and posteriorly, widely bare in between. Anepimeron entirely pilose. Katepimeron convex; bare. Wing: vein R4+5 without posterior appendix; vein M1 perpendicular to vein R4+5; postero-apical corner of cell r4+5 rectangular, with small appendix; crossvein r-m located between basal 1/8 to 1/4 of cell dm. Abdomen oval or kite-shaped, 1.2 to 2 times as long as wide. Tergites 3 and 4 fused. Sternite 1 pilose. Male genitalia: phallus furcate near apex, with dorsal process in some species a little longer than ventral process; epandrium with or without ventrolateral ridge.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="377EBEA71601E6326A935F7086DEED0B" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0CDD2D2762915CCF71CC3FCCE0FEB79F" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C5F3CDC38264EA5D7ADF0ADA569FC876" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Vein R4+5 without posterior appendix. Crossvein r-m located between basal 1/8 and 1/4 of cell dm. Subcostal vein joins costal vein after level of crossvein r-m. Postpronotum pilose. Abdomen oval or kite-shaped (tergite 2 wide, subsequent tergites triangularly narrowing). Antenna as long as or shorter than distance between antennal fossa and anterior oral margin. Basoflagellomere not furcate. Occiput narrow in dorsal half (usually also in ventral half, except in 
<taxonomicName id="91602EC9323FEB753BF77B0FDDF431C6" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus ulopodus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ulopodus">Hypselosyrphus ulopodus</taxonomicName>
Hull, 1944).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0284792EAFEE4D6BE773F3B98A1B70A3" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0DF55DC1EB702BB4081175779DA5FC53" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="429AF02F8C0EE46EFC48E7077B809B3F" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
When 
<bibRefCitation id="D48C8CDFAE6490F545DF6F6DFB660A6A" author="Hull, FM" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="12 - 32" title="New species of exotic syrphid flies." url="10.1155/1937/46960" volume="44" year="1937 a">Hull (1937a)</bibRefCitation>
erected the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4E9D2698806A0F8A22B0DE64E6B4C48D" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypselosyrphus</taxonomicName>
for his species trigonus, he mentioned its similarity to 
<taxonomicName id="FF9B990B20630B1223A6602EA2B9F5BB" authority="Walker, 1852" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ubristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ubristes" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ubristes</taxonomicName>
Walker, 1852 species, without clearly stating the differences. In his key to the groups of 
<taxonomicName id="7843DD1F63C9ADE9B6E7F9B14D7EE89F" lsidName="" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Microdontinae">Microdontinae</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="AEEB3C1F6B2AECC6DA3A89E8D1F77A48" author="Hull, FM" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Zoological Society" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="257 - 408" title="The morphology and inter-relationships of the genera of syrphid flies, recent and fossil." url="10.1111/j.1096-3642.1949.tb00224.x" volume="26" year="1949">Hull (1949)</bibRefCitation>
separated these taxa by the absence (
<taxonomicName id="9DDADEB627F996B86A994DADB8B46191" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypselosyrphus</taxonomicName>
) or presence (
<taxonomicName id="715F54BE3954972FC60122D1B9FA5715" authority="Walker, 1852" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ubristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ubristes" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ubristes</taxonomicName>
) of an appendix on vein R4+5. This character serves well to separate 
<taxonomicName id="9A8FF2E8C4BE1722B46C078D565F6AC1" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypselosyrphus</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="5BC023302FC86A43CD049342FAC813EA" authority="Walker, 1852" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ubristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ubristes" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ubristes</taxonomicName>
s.s. as defined in the present paper, and almost always for 
<taxonomicName id="A3B80530DFB8F549CC8C659574EBC90B" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Stipomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stipomorpha" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stipomorpha</taxonomicName>
(appendix on vein R4+5 seldomly missing), which was included in 
<taxonomicName id="4C88FB3C641B7A4D91F6C8D2BD3B2C07" authority="Walker, 1852" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ubristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ubristes" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ubristes</taxonomicName>
until now. In later keys and catalogues, 
<taxonomicName id="13230158B150783FB63404B35B4D1804" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypselosyrphus</taxonomicName>
was treated as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="DCA7EB0150038A65F43B1E6EE9AD1DE0" authority="Walker, 1852" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ubristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ubristes" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ubristes</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="1E58E4CBA6A1F500D637031B7E2D3C2F" author="Thompson, FC" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" pagination="74 - 85" title="A new genus of Microdontine flies (Diptera: Syrphidae) with notes on the placement of the subfamily." url="10.1155/1969/62102" volume="76" year="1969">Thompson 1969</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="7D53D6D0C1BACBEC5CF85974FBA1DFD9" author="Thompson, FC" journalOrPublisher="A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" pagination="1 - 195" title="Family Syrphidae." volume="46" year="1976">Thompson et al. 1976</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="FAED84F64060606E968C77DE92147A3E" author="Cheng, X-Y" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" pagination="21 - 48" title="A generic conspectus of the Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae) with the description of two new genera from Africa and China." volume="1879" year="2008">Cheng and Thompson (2008)</bibRefCitation>
also considered 
<taxonomicName id="42CF8A08496CE30359183BCEF26E39FD" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypselosyrphus</taxonomicName>
(and 
<taxonomicName id="EFC58AA1AEC8664B96D7BF83FA91B344" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Stipomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stipomorpha" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stipomorpha</taxonomicName>
Hull, 1945) synonymous with 
<taxonomicName id="DC363CEEA39EB008005A2B0BDEE684BA" authority="Walker, 1852" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ubristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ubristes" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ubristes</taxonomicName>
, but nevertheless differentiated the groups in their key. They consider abdominal shape to be diagnostic: oval or rectangular in 
<taxonomicName id="D3622244AA86852FE9F21DA6166545F8" authority="Walker, 1852" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ubristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ubristes" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ubristes</taxonomicName>
, short, almost equilaterally triangular in 
<taxonomicName id="38440F88A09D5E0EA9566C788E054C9A" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypselosyrphus</taxonomicName>
, much 
<pageBreakToken id="772EE1690A9DAF87E078338EE8AF14E6" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" start="start">longer</pageBreakToken>
, isosceles triangular in 
<taxonomicName id="571EF97508E0365A6A8E763BD0975AFE" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Stipomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stipomorpha" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stipomorpha</taxonomicName>
. As there are many varieties in abdominal shape among the the taxa involved, it is hard to decide where to draw the line. Other characters are necessary to distinguish these taxa satisfyingly (see key and diagnoses).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7FC060FC9758F18CE050CBC89F1331B1" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C923AECAFE7CB8D9E86FD570DFE2A3D7" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Diversity and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A2C0CB09A2C9C3EC9367AC174E5AD48" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Described species: 11. Descriptions of five additional species are in preparation by the first author. 
<taxonomicName id="5AAFF9EA5B84799BF065293D5F539860" authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hypselosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypselosyrphus</taxonomicName>
is known from Panama, the Amazon region and southern Brazil. Considering the small number of specimens known, it seems likely that the genus is widespread in tropical South America.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
